n still hear the voices of my troops, calling out my name for their next objective. I still see rows and rows of tanks on the roads to certain doom, just so that they can satisfy me. And- oh god.. The artillery. The MRLS... The apaches... All those units, all those points gone in an instant, for what? Fame? Bragging rights? Money?I'm going to have to leave now. My army calls me. I leave you with this message: Don't be like me. Don't be the guy sitting on his♥♥♥♥♥writing reviews for a video game for humorous effect. Don't overdose so much on Wargame. Go outside and ride a bike or something.I'm Gucci Gilgamesh, and I approve this message."
76561198354928672,Not Recommended,251060,31342454,Posted: 24 April,all,lopezec007,"This is hands-down the finest RTS ever made.  The level of detail and sheer complexity (and associated learning curve) are unmatched.  Other reviews cover this well though so I won't elaborate on this.After playing 700+ games (on a different Steam account), I must say though that it suffers from a horribly fatal flaw -- you can see the statistics of other players in the lobbies.  Why is this a problem?  Team stacking.  It's horrendous -- I might have played one game in ten that was balanced.  With all the others, the ""smart"" players (myself included), click around to see which team is better, then go to that team.  And the cycle repeats until you get a team of noobs against a team with 5000+ games of experience between them.  This leads to other problems.  It can sometimes take 30+ minutes to fill a lobby, as skilled players join the team destined to lose, realize it, and quit.  Or they linger hoping a spot on the to-win team opens up, then quit en masse right before the game starts.  Or anonymous lobby hosts will kick newer players and people they aren't buddies with off of the stacked team.If Eugen simply removed this option -- the ability to see the win ratios and game counts of other players -- this game would be very near perfect."
