,Recommended,251060,22922962,"Posted: 12 May, 2016",all,SuicideKing,"Initially played single player and bounced off the game after a while, but got back into it after I started playing with the folks I play Arma with.Pretty interesting game, encourages and rewards knowledge of weapon systems and has a rock-paper-scissiors way of doing things. If you understand this system, then you'll be good at it. Has micromanagement but not Men of War level of micro, so it's not too bad. Not a traditional RTS so don't buy this expecting Rise of Nations!Naval is probably underutilised in our games.Not too demanding on performance, more GPU bound. I'd recommend at least a GTX 560 or equivalent for 1080p.TL;DR: Recommended if you have a bunch of people to play with. General public community is quite weird, I find.EDIT: I successfully ran the game with Intel HD4600 Graphics when my 560 died. It runs well if you let it auto-detect settings, even though it won't look pretty when zoomed in. It's quite fluid with a 650 Ti BOOST and doesn't appear to want more than 2GB VRAM at 1080p."
,Recommended,251060,30987431,Posted: 6 April,all,Richard,"After about 8 hours played, it's clear that this game is absolutely mind-blowing. It's basically Total War: Modern Warfare. But way more in-depth and complex than anything in Total War. Hundreds of real world units, and you have to manage your actions down to tiny details like making sure your tanks face forwards, and retreat in reverse etc. Units have weak spots on their armour (such as the back of a tank) etc, and using smart tactics can turn a battle around in seconds. There is far too much to explain here, but I highly recommend this to any fan of strategy games, this is absolutely one of the best I've played.Reading some guides is highly recommended. The 1000-page guide on Steam is a good place to start.If you want a detailed, realistic modern RTS with spectacular gameplay and visuals, plus competitive multiplayer and a truly demented community of psychotic nationalists, this game is for you.Protip: don't take the community seriously. Kim Jong-Un and Donald Trump like to have fun in their spare time too."
