76561198129640167,Recommended,251060,24356294,"Posted: 16 July, 2016",all,Blue Embers,"First, if you enjoy RTS games, this is one you will definitely enjoy whether you like campaigns or multiplayer.The first most important things in regard to first playing is that there is a learning curve, and its pretty steep. For many, few games offer the dynamics or air and land comat with the lethality and speed that WG does, and remains blanced and fair. That boils down towards, if you want a game that is slower paced, it may not be for you,Having over 400 hours, i can say i am well acquainted with the pors and cons of the games design, and firstly i'd want to ring up the campaigns. There is a few scnearies with the last two being expansive and very long. Theyre great and ultimately they turn out the way you craft your forces to tackle the problem. Every time you play it, it ill turn out somewhat differantly which makes the games replayability remarkable. The downside is that the game compensates the poor intelligence of the AI with spam, and that spam is typically utilizing superior units, and those you can match are hard to replace when lost. it's incredibly easy to lose and unfortunately i've had to reload previous saves in order to actually win. The end result overall is still a great experience well worth your money alone.Second is the multiplayer. The multiplayer is similar to the campaign with its owns ups and downs. The first most obvious and great thing is your ability to hand craft your pre-set battle group or ""deck"". It allows you to play however you choose. It again requires a degree of understanding the game. When that is reached though, the creative and dynamic limits are only limited by you. This paired with other players doing the same leads to games where the outcomes are wildly varied. This is where the game really is worth your money. It is the reason why i can comeback time and again over games like Fallout 4 and other titles that are immedialtely boring after only a single playthrough.There are huge negatives which i Eugen needs to address though. The first is lobby stacking. The greatest problem that turns me away is the ability for experienced players to simply stack into one side of the team and wait for the lobby to fill up essentially gauranteeing a win. This is literally game breaking, and anyone new to the game will immediately realize after a dozen loses that the game is against them. It is a terrible and unfair system and isnt fun. If this wasnt an issue, the game would easily be a 9 out of 10,Everything altogether though, this game is brilliantly designed and encourages varied strategies and dynamic mindsets to counter and succeed against real people or computer AI's. Aside from its quirks, its well worth your money."
,Recommended,251060,33665204,Posted: 19 July,all,RedRapture,"The game is a well made game. It's very pretty, battles can get very intense, and there are tactics you need to learn in order to survive in the game. The maps are well designed and the campaigns have believable stories behind them. The community also isn't as bad as communities in other games. There's a good deal of military and political talk in chat, but mostly it remains civil. All in all, it's a good game that has more good than bad, so I can recommend it. However, there are several things lacking...- The economy for unit summoning is out of whack for the stated goal of ultra realism (Abrams, I'm looking at you). American and Soviet units cost the most to deploy on the battlefield, an attempt by the developers to not have the game dominated by those two armies. However, the time period WAS dominated by those two armies, and they had the capability to deploy their best units (M1A1 and A2 Abrams tanks, T90's, F-15's and 16's, MiG 29's) in vast quantities. This simply is not represented well in the game's battles. You can do better as North Korea than you can as the Soviet Union because of this. That being said, I've had some AWESOME battles where it's, say, Israel and France against China and North Korea.- The AI is not programmed well. In fact, it's programmed like AI were programmed back in the early 2000's. It knows exactly where your units are down to the last soldier. As soon as you fire upon it, all your forces are immediately 'visible' to the AI, even if they wouldn't be to a player, and attacked overwhelmingly. The AI acts like a player using hacks to see all your units and give itself infinite resources. Harder difficulty levels don't mean more advanced algorithms are used. No, harder difficulty levels mean more buffs for resources and unit stats for the AI.- There's no taking into account some of the superior technological strengths of either side. Units are balanced for a more arcadey feel. For example, NATO tanks have thermal optics that allowed them to see through smokescreens at the time represented in this game. However, because the Soviets did not have this tech, the tech is not represented in game.- Aircraft performance is still completely idiotic. For example, the aircraft do not naturally try to evade a missile on their own when fired upon, as a real piloted aircraft would regardless of what orders you give. And ground attack fighters armed with specialized anti-tank weapons will abandon the battlefield too early (A-10, I'm looking at you). THey'll expend their missiles then break off and RTB without using their anti-tank gatling guns. And, going into anti-air, you will NOT see any dogfights. The jets do not go to engage each other and enter into spectacular dogfights. No, they fire their long range missiles, and once those are dry, they strafe at each other. Think ye olde knights in a jousting tournament.Despite these flaws, it is a fun game, especially when you play it with friends, once you figure out how to actually succeed."
