76561198045820915,Recommended,251060,12920194,"Posted: 12 November, 2014",all,Wolf In Arms,"Right, so: I'm gonna forworn the reader that I'm not, like a lot of other reviewers might be, a long-term Wargame fan. In fact, this is my first Wargame-...erm, game, ever bought and played.But played, I have.I'd come into Wargame originally from RUSE: another game out of the Eugen box. As for RUSE, it served as a wonderful experience for me: I've sunk in hundreds of hours into it throughout a total of about three to four years. And especially for my version being an X-Box port purchased before I really had a gaming PC, me still playing RUSE on occasion to this day helps cement how wonderful it is.So understandably, I came into Wargame: Red Dragon with high expectations of perhaps my favorite Strategy Games studio. I'd become legitimately hyped on the trailers, and I'd always wanted to try out European Escalation or AirLand Battle.I'm not going to lie: this was a weird game to get into when it first game out. There were no in-game tutorials and no singleplayer, making the current lack of a dedicated tutorial mode (to my knowledge) a cubscout picknick in comparison. I had to teach myself how to manuever units through a private MP lobby, and that was a difficult task when I had no idea how complicated the controls in Wargame were.There were thankfully at least a few good and decent guides out there, but for other Wargames of course: thankfully, since I purchased it, a number of Red Dragon guides have arrived both from Eugen and from the vast community of players.To summarize getting into the game, it's difficult even today. It's a heavy difficult curb, but that's also what makes it wonderful: Red Dragon is AS REAL AS IT CAN GET, by all assumption. Playing Wargame is a legitimate way to learn a little more about how real warfare tactics, at least from the Cold War era, were like (to a limited extent, of course). Eugen put a lot of effort into making this game flow smoothly in terms of both difficulty placed on the computer and on the player's own abilities: while your computer is going along just fine with relatively impressive and immersive graphics, you're trying your damn best to keep up-to-speed in an MP game.There's also a large amount of singplayer capability as well: the uniqueness that the deck system provides (perhaps my favorite piece of this whole game) not only allows for the common joke of players spending more time on deck/army building than on playing the game, but also allowing for players to have their own customized adventures and battles.In addition, there are a decent number of singleplayer campaigns set during various points in the Cold War. These campaigns are decent in story and certainly immersive, and provide a really interesting challenge for the player. Of course, these aren't really the good meat of the game.As for the multiplayer: it's really the main bit, though not required. I'd still recommend anyone buying Wargame to try out MP at least a few times per month to continually improve battlefield skill and preformance. It's honestly interesting to watch a deck go into combat, and to analyize how one could've preformed better and which parts of the deck went by the ""make or break"" principle.In addition, it must be added that Eugen consistently releases free DLC. FREE DLC. THAT YOU AUTOMATICALLY GET. This includes new maps, new units, and new campaigns. How consumer-friendly is that?As for complaints, they're predominately based around the gameplay mechanics and are mostly deck-based. For starters, I play as an American deck and understand that nations are weak in some areas based on historical weakness (E.G. North Korea having relatively poor anti-aircraft abilities in comparrison to some of its allies). However, a few instances of favoritism seem to pop up with the French: a nationality which Eugen is part of, as a French studio. For one, the French are capitalized on favoring quick and mobile strikes, though in reality their units can preform a number of tasks *extremely* well. French Infantry AT weapons are some of the best in the game towards the 90's era, French tanks are relatively powerful, French aircraft are highly potent in all areas, French helicopters are some of the fastest and most combat-effective, and so-on. France has downsides, but very few in comparison to some of its counterparts and enemies: thus, it could seen that France has been given some relative favoritism by Eugen, but I digress.In addition, another complaint perhaps could be leveled at the lack of a very solid training mode for beginners. I know that I myself would've loved access to a dedicated training mode when I first started, and a flip-through guide isn't going to help with learning units outside of a textbook fashion.To summarize....Pros:-Decent Graphical Fidelity and Running Capability-Excellent Customization Capacity-Immersive, Authentic and Risk-Taking Gameplay-Decently-Captivating Campaign-Free DLCCons:-Eurocentric Favoritism, potentially-Lack of Newbie Integration and TutorialsIn short: a highly-recommended game."
,Recommended,251060,15365212,"Posted: 14 April, 2015",all,ToughPancke,"Lots of red, no dragons."
,Recommended,251060,9965848,"Posted: 28 April, 2014",all,k9catforce,"Ever dream of being a great tacticion, but don't really want to join the military? Here's your answer. Hard, but really really fun when your plans actually work out. It'll kick your butt in the beginning, but you get used to it after a while."
76561197998164472,Recommended,251060,14539085,"Posted: 18 February, 2015",all,Evil Dinner Fork,"From a newcomer with no experience with the prior games, but one who has been obsessing with this one for the past 3 days or so: Wargame is an amazing endeavour and is one of the most in-depth RTS's on Steam.The Wargame series is heavily influenced by World In Crisis, another WWIII RTS, and if you've played that game, you'll be familiar with the broad strokes. The biggest difference is one of scale. In WiC, an armored commander will end up controlling maybe 3-4 heavy tanks and a couple other random units once he's maxxed out. In Wargame, a player with an armored deck (more on decks in a minute) will *start* the game with maybe 8 heavy tanks, or else mass hordes off lesser or obsolete tanks, in addition to support... and it goes up from there. The maps are also truly massive, with even the smaller ones roughly 100km by 100km and going up from there -- the scale is more in line with the first Supreme Commander. Within that vast distance, even specialized commanders must jostle with multiple control groups of their frontline guys, recon, supply/logistics (this is a big one), air defense, and so forth.Like WiC, the game is built around hard counters, with even the mightiest unit reduced to scrap in seconds if it meets its counter. The key is recon, to know what the enemy has and where, so that you may counter it. Are they sending in mass hordes of tanks? If your recon spots it in time, you can counter with helis or Maverick-armed AT planes. Does the enemy have an assload of AA? Keep your helis/planes far away, and charge your own armor or light vehicles in. Do they have a bioball of massed infantry in a town? Time for your arty to step up -- or even better, napalm-equipped units. All of this depends on having good recon to know what counter you need to bring onto the field.As far as the much-derired naval content goes: Yes, I'm sure the pure-navy maps suck. But coastline maps are where your navy shines. You do not command capital ships in this game -- think more along the lines of patrol boats. And every deck gets free naval units the player may build if he chooses. Completely ignoring the water parts of these maps is a valid strategy, letting you concentrate everything on your land and air; but on the other hand, owning the water denies the shoreline to the enemy, and the heavy AA of most ships gives you an excellent no-fly zone.I mentioned supply and logistics. All units have only limited ammo, some more limited than others; all units besides infantry also have fuel; and, naturally, units need healing after taking damage in combat. Supply units take care of all these needs, but the supply units are all vulnerable and die if an enemy even looks at them wrong. This adds an extra dimension to combat not found in most of these games.The graphics are servicable, and are mostly enjoyed in replays. In-game, you will be too busy to enjoy them, similar to Supreme Commander: you're zoomed-out, dealing with icons. Sounds are also basic and servicable; unit prompts are always in the unit's tongue.As far as decks go: this is one of the greatest innovations of the game. A deck is the selection of units you bring into a match. Decks can be generalist, or (in the spirit of WiC) focused on armored, air, etc; focused decks give you bonuses to focused units at the expense of reduced options everywhere else. You can draw units from the entirety of your faction (NATO + Japan/S.Korea, or else WarPac + China/N.Korea), or you can limit yourself to just a few or even one nation for further bonuses at the cost of, again, reduced options. (Want to play as Denmark fighting against the Soviet Union? This game has your back!) You can and will spend hours simply building various ""decks"" you can bring into a game.The AI is servicable, but limited. It will keep a new player on their toes, but its quirks will soon be learned by even the novice. It ""fast moves"" on roads too much; it never buys ships on coastal maps; it seems confused on what to do with infantry. On the other hand, it can build a mean armored column that will take you by surprise and back it up with gunships and AA. If you want the AI fighting at its best, give it a more armored and support-focused deck that neglects infantry.On that note, it should be mentioned that the multiplayer community of this game is filled with racists and ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥s. You are better off with people you know IRL.Anyway, if you are looking for an incredibly deep RTS with a steep learning curve, yet one that eschews the APM-centric style of most RTS's, you've come to the right place."
