,Recommended,251060,10322609,"Posted: 2 June, 2014",all,Maxwell Sinclair,"Ok this is going to be a long one so settle in.I would recommend this game, very much so, but it is not for everyone. So you really must sit down and ask yourself some questions before you purchase this game.1. Do you want a simple RTS?2. Do you like base building?If your answer is yes to either of these, then this game will not be for you. There is no base building and it is certainly not simple. This game is micro management heavy and it attempts realism, which can be a touch complicated for new players, its tutorials do not explain much.3. Do you own Wargame Airland Battle?If yes, go and play that, don't buy this until it comes on sale. If anything it is something of a downgrade from the past generation, the deck building is different and limited, the naval units are pretty lacking and there is no naval diversity.Ok now I'll get the petty problems I have with this game out of the way, note they're personal opinion, take them as you will.The deck building has been dumbed down, you get significantly less cards to use in any one type of unit unless you specialise your deck into a specific type such as airborne or armored. The mechanic for nations have changed and limiting yourself to an era is not as useful as before. To put that into perspective.In AirLand Battle, limiting your deck to one nation gave you prototype units for that nation, and based on the tech level of the nation, it granted you extra points to deploy units with.  Specializing gave extra experience to certain unit types and made some cheaper (Motorized: +1 XP level for infantry, -1 activation cost for planes.) Limiting yourself to an era gave you more availability for units, as in, you could get a significant percentage more for the same price. each unit type had 9 spaces for cards, getting progressively more expensive.In this game, limiting yourself to a nation grants you the Prototypes but also has an effect on the availability. Specializing limits you to certain types but gives you extra room for cards in specific types as well as changing the Xp and Costs. Limiting oneself to an era simply provides you with bonus activation points. Oh and you only get 5 spaces for cards in each unit type unless you specialized.Limiting yourself to an era is almost useless on account of the fact that you can often not find enough units to use up all the cards you earned and if you can they're often so paper thin that anyone who did not limit themselves to an era will walk all over your deck with their own.Sorry this is taking so long but there is a lot to say.The naval units added to the game are so underwhelming and useless that it is almost not worth bothering with them, thankfully they cost 0 activation points to add to your deck, they do still cost deployment points though. Anywho the nations are placed under 2 flags. BLUFOR and REDFOR, NATO and PACT (Plus the extra countries) respectively. Each nation shares the same navy so the only diversity you have is between the BLUFOR and REDFOR ships, no matter what nation you choose. The ships available are fairly disappointing, there are frigates, gunboats and a couple of destroyers (The biggest ships in the game) oh and a few helicopters and planes that are navy specific. There are some maps with rivers on them, which river boats can make use of IF there is a naval corridor in the game.That is a big problem for me, if you want to use your navy, you have to have a map with a naval corridor, meaning there has to be this huge expanse of open ocean, which is something the games AI ignores, I've seen it countless times in a match, the AI captures its naval corridor, then refuses to deploy navy from it, so you end up with a one sided ocean where you own it. The one thing I do use the ships for, is to repel the AI's nature for helicopter spamming. The larger ships have Radar Missiles that work rather well against helicopters. The AI will spam your ships with artillery and aircraft when it spots them though which can be annoying but also good since you can lure it into a trap. The one useful thing is that you can use the naval corridors to deploy extra ground units, these range from infantry to artillery and even a few tanks and even some supply vehicles. They'll be depolyed via landing craft, so it still requires the naval corridor to use them.Next problem is also related to the navy. Would someone kindly kick Eugen systems in the anoose and tell them that naval craft, particularly large ships, have indirect fire cannons, not direct fire ones. The navy would be incredibly useful if the 100 and 135mm cannons they mounted could be fired like offshore artillery. Instead you have to have a shore line with no buildings and no forests in the way if you want to shoot at anything on the land. I find myself only using one actual ship for each team. The BLUFOR one has rediculously good ECM and a lot of radar based missiles for shooting down aircraft. The REDFOR one is a small little gunboat with rocket artillery attached to the back, which is about the only offshore artillery in the game, and personally I enjoy offshore artillery.Ok sorry to put you through all that, but if you're going to make an informed decision you may as well know the biggest points I find wrong with the game. Now for some positives.The game tries to be realistic and for an RTS game it does it rather well, it is a fair bit more complex than simply building a fortress then churning out units to throw into the meat grinder.The units are period accurate and well detailed, the whole game is really nice to look at actually.The unit variation for the most part is quite nice, I know it looks like there are repeats but each one has a different weapon or an update to a current one.The deck building is still fun, although different, often you can spend hours creating various decks to play in various strategies. before playing with themThe AI is still hyper agressive and it can seem overwhelming at first, but it is predictable so you can learn to plan around it. The Mutliplayer is a fair bit of fun as long as you have friends to play it with.All in all I would recommend this game but I would recommend giving it serious consideration before purchasing it, if you're already a veteran of the series and you've played the others, then I would recommend letting this game go until it comes on sale. I consider it worth the purchase, but not worth the $40 they charge for it.Sorry to make you read all that."
