,Not Recommended,251060,11143489,"Posted: 8 July, 2014",all,Prime Minister Sinister,"Wargame: Red Dragon will certainly come off a dissapointment to most AirLand Battle players, and while it isn't terrible, there aren't many reasons I could think of to recommend this game over AirLand Battle, especially for its hefty pricetag.To go into detail, let's look at what the game gets right. There is a huge roster expansion, with many new vehicles, factions, and maps. Sadly, most of these new units are reskins of existing ones, but this is true to life, so Eugen deserves some lee-way. The maps are massive and expansive. I am not sure if they are bigger than AirLand Battle, but it sure felt like it. Logistics is more important, as vehicles run out of fuel much quicker and the bigger maps also eat up more fuel. It is an interesting system that adds a dynamic to the game that we haven't seem previously, as going after supply vehicles will actually damage the enemy greatly.Now let us talk about where it goes wrong. Oh, there are so, so many ways this game goes wrong. First and formost is that they screwed up the deck building system. Now, when you make a deck, there are only five open unit slots, where as previous games held all 10 open for use for any deck. The problem is that the game forces you to use specialized decks, but specialization is a bad idea. What if you happen to bring a specialized deck that is vulnerable to the enemy's deck type? Well, you're screwed. The five slots prevent you from making a well-rounded deck. I get they wanted people to have incentive for using specialized decks, but this was not the way to do it. They should provide postive reinforcement for choosing to specialize, like making the bonuses for specialized decks greater (and making their unit restrictions less harsh: many units that certain specializations exclude you from don't even fit into the opposing category, meaning it just removes units for no reason), not by removing stuff that made normal decks good.Balance is all over the ♥♥♥♥ing place. AirLand Battle struck a nice balance, with only the jets being a little overpowered. Now that is flipped on its head. One SAM (or Redfor equivalent) can easily pummel a jet. Sure, anti-air availability has been cut, and so has their ammo, but now planes are weak as♥♥♥♥♥♥and they rarely even reach their traget. They are just a good way of wasting money. Infantry is also useless. Before, putting infantry in buildings was an effective way to ensure that area of the map was basically yours, unless your enemy used specific anti-infantry vehicles to counter. Infantry are now weaker. They die quicker, and their weapons are far less effective against heavy armor. They are, however, cheap. The worst thing is artillery. I don't know what the ♥♥♥♥ went through Eugen's Systems combined heads when they thought of making artillery more destructive. Artillery is supposed to be a support tool used for bogging down and enemy and lowering their morale in preparation for a ground attack, but in Red Dragon they are an offensive tool that can snipe units from across the map and continuously pound just about anything (and I do mean anything) to death. Entrentched infantry? Dead meat. Top-teir armor? Be gone after 3 salvos. Even helicopters can get ruined by these things. It is such an abysmal decision and it ruins a game like this, where arguably balance is everything.Then there are navies. actual, proper ship on ship warfare can be fun, but there really isn't much to it. Whoever has more ships wins. You can spam extremely ♥♥♥♥♥♥, low-level ships, but nothing will get through their output of fire.These changes completely ruin this game and remove any fun from it. It is replaced with frustration, as opponents cheekily snipe you from across the map (including the all-seeing AI) with artillery, amass fleets of♥♥♥♥♥♥teir boats and tear through everything you have, and make the airforce a complete waste of time and money.I thought Red Dragon would be fun because of the new units and setting, but I just got a ♥♥♥♥♥♥, unbalanced version of AirLand Battle that does not do justice to its predecessor. ALB is more well-rounded and balanced, and it is altogether more fun. Don't be tricked by fanboys throwing heaps of praise on this game, and don't waste your money. By ALB or EE.As a sidenote, there is ONE group of people I can recommend this game to. RD has the easiest and most fair AI of all the Wargame titles. That doesn't mean it is easy or fair, it just means it is actually ♥♥♥♥ing beatable. So if you are mostly a singleplayer type of guy, you should probably pick this up."
,Recommended,251060,25445883,"Posted: 10 September, 2016",all,Name nomad,I didn't know this was more than just chat until two weeks ago.
76561197986365521,Recommended,251060,19327212,"Posted: 27 November, 2015",all,Diarrhea Cactus,"Re-review below main review now that I have clocked some more time.  See botom if interested for latest updates.=============================================================================Wargame Red Dragon is the game I have been looking for since giving up on my 200+ hours of Company of Heroes 2 and 300+ of Company of Heroes 1 (prior to the stupid Steam edition).  This game is about tactics and understanding what is happening on the battlefield while changing your thought process on the fly.  You can't just spam out 15,000 infantry and win the game.  Tanks, anti-air/infantry, and jets will eat you alive.  Spam tanks and end up in the same situation.  The game encourages a combined arms.  Now there is some spam, as the bloc countries rely more on quantity than quality versus the allied west/NATO nations.There are around 1700 units in the game and some of them are very similar to each other but have their unique niche that they fill.  I'm only 10 hours in and know nothing of what I am supposed to be doing other than relying mroe on quantity since I play primarily Russia with a side of North Korea.  From WW2 tanks to about 1991, there are plenty of vehicles, tanks, infantry, air, and navy.  From the VDV, Spetsnaz to the T80, it's all here on the bloc side of things.  The Japanese, Canadian, US, and myriad of other allied/NATO nations are also playable.From a gameplay perspective you build a deck of units that you will choose prior ot launching the game. These units are all you get, once they are gone that is it.  No base building just pure calling in troops from off the map based on whatever entrance they get.  Sometimes when you cap points you can call in units from a nearby edge of the map.  Units have tons of stats and rank up as they survive and do well.  Don't ask me what the ideal setup for stats are because their probably isn't one or if there is, I am entirely too new to understand or know yet.Sound, graphics, and gameplay are all top notch.  If you liked Ruse you will like this.  If you want to play with people, the commnity might be a bit rough.  I bought this to play with friends agains the AI as that is what we do to have a good time.  To each their own!There are a myriad of maps to play and tons of AI levels to go up against.  The AI does tend to ""cheat"" in that it knows what the yare up against but with the proper planning it is easy to deal with and just makes the game more interesting.  It isn't Company of Heroes 2 cheating where they can call in smoke abilities every 15 seconds for free.  Tactics win the game every time.  When you loose to a 2v1 AI you know you are terible!I'd like to recommend this game to anyone that is looking into getting an RTS that is more modern day and requires thought and planning and not spamming one unit like other RTS games out there.  This one is good.  Fuel and ammo play an integral role and without resupply, your tanks will either stop dead or just not be able to do anything.  The realism is kept at a high level without compromising gameplay.  Is the game worth 40 dollars?  I think so but I would still prefer to get it on sale and this Christmas as well as this weekend it is on sale!  Do yourself a favor and add a game to your library you can get some major hours out of!=============================================================================Updated Review:Most of what was said above still holds true.  I still am learning many things about the game and am far from even considering playing against people.  However, I have a new appreciation for this game that I didn't have previously.  As I learned more of the game's intricacies I fell more in awe of the game.Things such as higher grade ammo costing more to resupply and learning the intentions of the units beyond ""Go blow this up"" has really put more fun into the game.  Things like anti-tank helicopters being used incorrectly and wasting time and resources by blowing up vehicles with them instead of tanks (unless they are spamming vehicles)  has enlightmened me to proper deck building.  No longer do I sent in maximum penetration tanks to wipe out vehicles unless they happen to be there.  Positioning, morale, hitpoints (the blue boxes under the unit info), and how they are affected by things blowing up around them is amazing.Furthermore, recon, recon, recon, recon!  Learn to know what you are up against.  There is nothing worse than building a force that isn't ideal against whatever the opponent has.  Learning the special types of jets for anti-air vheicles, the fire and full reverse to reload concept, and keeping your guns cold on recon are all aspects I didn't even consider because I was so used to Starcraft, Warcraft, Company of Heroes, etc.This game takes realism to the limit without ruining the experience.  I appreciate this game so much more as a result.   The only aspect of the game that I think needs some work is the navy.  It seems like it's rather broken at the moment and naval battles are more or less, a waste of time and effort.  Outisde of that, this game continues to impress me and offer a different experience everytime I play.============================================================================="
