76561198068838398,Recommended,251060,20854438,"Posted: 30 January, 2016",all,The ultimate sin is cum denial,"Probably one of the most interesting games I've ever played. Just the units alone make this game garner my attention. There's 1200+! And the gameplay really is a perfection of the RTS gimic of countering. Every unit has a counter, but some counters are better than others, and it's that split-second decision of not only picking counters, but also attacking and defending, that really gives this game it's charm. However, this game certainly isn't perfect. The naval battles basically consist of spamming as many large boats as you can, which really kind of takes away from the constraint of the land and air battles. The learning curve is pretty steep, which isn't helped by the pretty awful community. There is also a lot of rage-quitting in games, with little to no punisment for it. I love this game very much, and if either updates or a sequel could handle these problems, I would be very pleased."
,Recommended,251060,13561216,"Posted: 23 December, 2014",all,rYgel,"There's three games to the Wargame series, and in my opinion this is the best. A lot of people will disagree with me, and say that the 2nd; Air Land Battle was the best. However, this one here adds a completely new realm to the series; naval combat. I've played the second, and to this, this is much better. Not because of naval combat, but ""stuff"".The Red Dragon version is just into ""stuff"". You load up the game in some sort of military command room lit with ominous red lights and given 16,000 units to chose from. Yes. Sixteen thousand! Now, a lot of the units are just different units with different weapons, but I'd say 75% of them are completely modeled, textured, for their roll. Now, the issue I had when I loaded this up was to understand the difference between a ""USA Marine Stinger"" and a ""USA Marine Igla"" was. The two weapons are anti-air, have the same strength and so on. And you'll realize how confusing it is when you are juggling tons of units.The game play is completely different to all other RTS. You really need to coordinate with your team. Tell them to flank here or there, smoke a certain position to cover retreating units, send recon helicopters behind enemy lines near a mountain top and spot what ever they're doing. Don't expect to walk into a game and win. You'll either lose the ones you play, or just be carried by some amazing commander.The Campaign is lack luster. Not amazing. It's good for starting out, mainly for practice. But I would rather do skirmish battles. They're a little more fun, and you have more freedom. There isn't even a story so to speek.Would I reccomend this? Yes. It's a great game. I don't have much hours because I don't really have someone I can trust in a battle to protect me from getting flanked. And that's an issue you'll run into. Many unskilled players. So you either learn quickly, or dominate the other team.I'd get this if you want a change to most generic military RTS's out there. Just get ready for the incredable learning curve this game offers."
