,Recommended,251060,10194956,"Posted: 21 May, 2014",all,Dosedmonkey,"I am reviewing this as someone who has never played a game in the Wargame series before. And well I can tell you, buying this franchise now, when it has so much content is a fantastic experience, as everything is new to me.At first the game seems a little overwhelming, and you wonder how you are going to be able to concentrate on so many elements, and make tacticaly pushes at the same time. But after playing a few rounds of the game, and getting a couple of hours under your belt it becomes an addictive fever of how you can improve your army choice and their tactics of use. In this game you can create completely custom armys, with a choice of over 750 units per side, so thats over 1500 units in total. And you can put a combination of any of those 750 in to your army you want, or you can use a specific nation only, and if you want a specific role, airbourne, marine, mechanized, armoured, just some examples, and with these you will get bonuses, allowing you to field more units, not less, in your specialisations!I have only really played the British and USSR in any detail yet, although I have also created North Korean and Anzac (Australia & New Zeland) armys also. And well I can tell you, the choice of units you get, first seems overwhelming, but don't worry, pick something, try it out, after a game or two you will go, hang on, nope i prefer a longer range artillery type, or possibly you feel your vehicle anti air vehicles are to vunerable to being spotted and prefer to field infantry anti air in future. And this progression and refining is continual.I find 4v4 games enjoyable, but I find the 10 vs 10 games exciting, and thrilling, as ten people try to push and defend a line, and support one another, it feels a lot more unpredictable, and evolving and in the end realistic then any other RTS I have played. If you watched back many of the 10 vs 10 battles on video you would struggle sometimes to realise whos units are whos, and that it wasn't a real historical battle, the way lines are formed, holes found and pushed in the enemy lines, and weak spots reinforced in your own line.The only problem I have found with the game is when your team starts loosing, a lot of people will be quick to drop out of the game, which is rediculous as many times I have found you can fight back from a loosing position if you work together. I think there should be some form of punishing the statistics of those who quit out early. Okay the players resource points is shared out between players, but sometimes a team is only just slightly loosing, because they lost their harbour, and half of their team will quit, meaning micro management just got a lot harder! And even with half the team quit you got to give the guys sticking to it credit though, they fight on to the last fire base, and hold every inch of ground.I vow to be someone who never quits out of a game early because I am loosing. Its all about having good fun, gameplay, and in the finish, last stands can be great fun. You can hold them off to the end of the timer, it will be a draw often.Do not be put off by the lack of VOIP (Voice chat) in game, you will find the system, where you can type short messages and ping it, smoke tag a spot of ground, with the writing much more useful. You can quickly type ""Enemy AA"" or ""Enemy Arty"" and tag it on the enemy position. Or tag where you will capture, or what troops you are pushing on to a spot very quickly. And this is better then struggling to describe something on these huge battlefields some times.So in short, a great Real Time Stratergy game, if you haven't tryed this series of games yet and enjoy RTS games, I would say it is a must buy. A great experience, and a new level of large scale RTS. What are you waiting for, buy it!"
