76561198049546969,Recommended,251060,18347792,"Posted: 5 October, 2015",all,Willy McGuffin,"The most in-depth strategy game I've ever played.Eugen deserves some felicitations for the ambition manifested by this game and its engine. Despite the learning cliff, this game strikes the right balance between predictability and replayability. The UI is deceptively simple, and the complexity of the game owes more to tactics than any other single element. There is no base-building mechanic or resource collection to speak of here; all the units are at your fingertips right from the start, ensuring intensity from the beginning of each game.This is not an easy game to learn. Each unit has hard counters, many of which will not occupy the same price bracket. Tanks get a special mention not as invincible death machines, but simply as counters to enemy armour, which are themselves vulnerable to all kinds of threats, ranging from infantry to ATGMs to airstrikes. There is no unit that cannot be killed in one hit by another, far less expensive one. This means that Wargame can also be highly frustratinng at times. It also means that the ability to predict where your opponent is going to place their units is a skill to be valued. Coupled with a unique recon mechanic that completely eschews LOS bubbles and fog of war, this makes each round surprisingly tense. In many cases the only thing telling you whether a treeline contains an enemy squad or not will be your instinct. Expect to spend the better part of 50 games figuring out the basics. Watch replays or you will find yourself going up against and losing to the same formations again and again.Playing a match of Wargame is like conducting a symphony. Miscalculating maneuvers by mere seconds can mean you'll be picked apart. But when it all comes together- it's exhilerating, and there is nothing like it."
