,Recommended,251060,9672042,"Posted: 29 March, 2014",all,wwwwホホホホホハハハハハハハハ,"中国将越来越大If you're a fan of previous Wargame installations, Red Dragon is a must have. However, if you have no prior experience in the Wargame series but still insist on getting the game; be warned, the online learning curve is very steep.Wargame is a unique kind of Real-time Strategy game, differing from well-known RTS games like C&C or StarCraft in many aspects. Typical base building -- or rather, base building at all -- is absent, as are typical economic systems (i.e money, different resources and all that ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥t). The latter of which is replaced by a single, universal ""resource"", to which you use to bring units in from off screen.Wargame also incorporates more realistic mechanics into the game. Units will react to situations more realistically, for example, a tank company being bombarded by artillery or caught in a napalm strike will freak the ♥♥♥♥ out and try to escape from combat, disregarding orders in the process. Most units also have limited fuel and ammo, which will need to be resupplied to them. And projectiles act like projectiles would in real life, having chances to hit or miss a target, with factors like an obstructed line of sight coming into play.Now, as much as I love this game, I find that the naval combat -- one of the selling points of the game -- is unredeemably bland. As beautiful as it looks, there's almost no depth to it at all; it's a simple matter of ""huck enough missiles at the bad guys to kill them"". Unlike the aircraft mechanic which plays a pivotal role in the game, the naval combat's role is minor at best, but more commonly is downright trivial.Overall I give Wargame: Red Dragon a 8.5/10, Eugen definitely has not disappointed with the beautifully detailed battles that we've come to love from the Wargame series, but the not-so-subtle lack of depth from the naval combat is hard to overlook.Wargame: Red Dragon is amasochist'sCold War enthusiast's dream. A tough as hell RTS experience that somehow has you coming back for more. However, if you do plan on buying it, buy it for the multiplayer, singleplayer isn't even half the experience of the game.(P.S, this isn't a ""meh C&C"", think before you speak.)"
