,Recommended,251060,11008377,"Posted: 1 July, 2014",all,Dealman,"I think a friend of mine managed to summarize this game in a pretty clever way;This game is the ArmA of RTS games.And I wholeheartedly agree with the statement.IntroductionThis game is a very realistic RTS game based in a modern era(Though, it does have a few selections of WW2 assets, they don't do too well against modern assets. Who'd figure?).You'll be able to select between 2 factions; BLUFOR and REDFOR - but can also select a coalition within either faction. For example, you could play as the Commonwealth, NATO or even Scandinavia(Really appreciate the addition of Scandi!).One of the biggest aspects of this game is not only the sheer amount of units available at your disposal, but rather they way that you use them. Similar to card games, you'll need to build a deck.This Deck will consist of9categories;• Logistics(Supply and Command Vehicles)• Infantry• Support(Anti-Aircraft, Artillery and Mortars)• Tanks• Recon• Vehicles(Mostly consist of Jeeps, Light Armour - pretty much whatever isn't a MBT. Lots of TOW and ATGM)• Helo• Plane• NavalSo as you can see, you have a fair share of categories to build a deck out of. Of course you don'tneedto use all categories - but it is highly recommended. Because if you for example make a deck without anti-aircraft to support you, you'll be having a very, very bad time.When you create a deck, you'll also have the option to select bonuses. Basically what this does is limit the amount of cards you have, but in return for faster veterancy gain and availability.I won't go into detail on how this work, there's a very nicely written 200-page guide which cover each and every of your needs - while also having a little but of humour in it.First ImpressionsBeing a big fan of slow paced RTS games such as Total Annihilation, Supreme Commander and Command & Conquer, I wasn't quite sure what I was getting myself into. Honestly, I just bought the game cause it looked interesting and had some nice tanks I'm very fond of.My first impression of the game was something like; ""Wtf, no base building? LAME!"". This was one of my biggest complaints, but only since it was what I was used to. I then realized this isn't just like every other RTS game out there, this one is REALLY unique.I had a really hard time getting into the game, until now. Because of the other RTS games I had played, you grow this kind of habit to just spam the most powerful unit at your disposal and just overtake your enemy with brute force. You see, this does not work in this game - not at all.Every unit has something that counters that unit. The key of learning this game is something called Combined Arms. If you do not get used to Combined Arms, you will die. Horribly. Even by the Easy AI.That brings me to another topic; the AI.The AII usually find the AI to be a big disappointment in RTS games, especially since I'm not too fond of PvP in RTS games since mostly there's a select few tactics which are always the best way to go, and if you don't do either - you'll lose.I haven't really done any PvP in this game yet, since I'm still learning the basics against the AI. And I'll give credit where credit is due - the AI in this game isn't that bad.Especially for a game of such a scale, I find the AI to be rather competent. It's not the usual cheating AI you see in other RTS games where they get bonus income because they're an AI, they're not affected by fog of war because they're AI and so on. As far as I know, the AI doesn't have any handicaps(Correct me if I'm wrong!)[/i].Final VerdictAt first I'd probably rate this game a mere 4/10, simply because I couldn't get used to the fact it's extremely difficult to get into. But now that I've started to learn the basics, this game really does a great job at introducing a new kind of genre of RTS games - maybe I've missed some, but this is the only RTS game I've played which such a focus on realism.The interface is alright, there are some things that could be better. But the main menus for all W:ALB and W:RD look great and feel pretty immersive.You have a absolutely ridiculous amount of units available, you can fulfill whatever role you have ever wanted - either to great success or great failure - nonetheless, it's great fun to explore new things and build decks from scratch.I would highly recommend this game, but I'd also like to warn you;This game is extremely difficult to first get into. I would highly suggest you read the 200-page guide available BEFORE you play this game. Or else you'll with most likeliness end up not liking it, simply because you were a fool not to prepare.If I were to rate it, I'd give it a 9 out of 10. Losing 1 point because it does a♥♥♥♥♥♥poor job at introducing new players.The BadOf course, as with every game it does have its flaws here and there. Some of whichin my opinionare;• TOW and ATGM can feel a bit overwhelming. Both when used against your enemy and used by your enemy.• The game does a poor job at showing how to bed use infantry. Garrisoned infantry is wunderbar!• Scandinavian troops are pretty outdated, hopefully they'll be updated with some DLC in the future!• Some sound effects are really bad, most notably the infantry's firearms sound absolutely dreadful. Where as vehicles can sound very satisfying.• The maps feel really repetitive, just different landscape but usually the same amount of spread sectors. Maps with bridges can be great fun, though! Bottlenecks ftw!The SuggestionsReally all I'd want for this game is Scandinavian troops to be updated, since there's plenty of 1990+ units in some nations. Sweden has plenty of modern equipment from 1990 and above.Other than that, some things I'd like to see;• A more unique variety of maps, some with a tight spread of sectors, some very open ones.• Some maps with a GREAT focus on urban warfare, where infantry and IFVs wouldreallyshine. With this I mean perhaps a most mostly consiting of a city, with some forested outskirts.• More satisfying sound effects for infantry! Sounds like paintball for crying out loud..."
