,Not Recommended,251060,20056997,"Posted: 28 December, 2015",all,Joachim Murat,"Truely a WargameWargame: Red Dragon is a military enthusiast's dream. It places you in command of both Western and Eastern fighting forces in a series of hypothethical conflicts set in the 1990's with it's singleplayer campaign. With Red Dragon's multiplayer, you can also face off against other players in large scale, strategic battles with all sorts of military equipment. Artillery strikes will pound forests and towns into dusts as infantry companies are slaughtered in buildings. Tanks will crest hills only to be annihilated by airstrikes. Your army will be destroyed again, and again, and again in every circumstance.My biggest warning, and the ultimate reason why I do not recommend this game, is the mountain of a learning curve that it suffers from. The ingame tutorial is outright pointless, and user created guides for this game for newcomers are literally 200 pages long. You would face less difficulty in being a Soviet officer during the invasion of Finland than playing this game.My first experience in the beginner campaign was that of utter confusion. I have played one of Eugen Systems' earlier games, RUSE, which is very similar in style and presentation to this game, but I was still bumbling in the forest. You will see your units be destroyed again and again as you fumble with the UI and are subject to a hundred different game mechanics at once. Combined arms are the way to succeed in this game, but good luck figuring out how to even command your forces effectively, as you must study pages of statistics in order to decipher the barebones and lacking user interface.In this game, you must account for individual platoons taking towns while also making sure they are resupplied and well fed - but don't forget that you must also cover them with smoke at all times or else they will be vulnerable to enemy tank divisions. Hide your men in the forest - but wait, the enemy recon car spotted you! Now the forest is in flames as artillery barrages incinerate it. Quick, scramble your attack helicopters and jets to strike the enemy guns, but wait - the enemy has waves of anti aircraft weapons that will destroy your aircraft! It is a punishing experience in which you must act as the officer of every single element of an army. Even when in complete comprehension of the game mechanics, it is still a punishing and often frustrating experience nonetheless.I would only recommend this game to those who have played earlier installations of the Wargame franchise, or have the fortitude to withstand endless documentation and guidance on this game to learn it. For some, they will experience the enjoyment of a noble when playing this game - but for the rest of us, we will only toil as peasants to understand it."
