,Not Recommended,251060,14234071,"Posted: 29 January, 2015",all,nickj,"Red Dragon is a big disappointment. I'm not a fan of RTS games, preferring grand strategy, but I thought WGALB had enough to make an enjoyable mix and I wasn't disappointed with it. When I decided to upgrade, it was already with reservations but there seemed to be more content for Red Dragon, so I made the jump.What a mistake.Eugen have pumped up the game with flash videos and cosmetic touches but the gameplay has suffered massively. While the campaigns sound attractive, the new interface makes moving and assigning units to combat difficult and annoying. Just when you think you've got the rigth mix of forces committed to a fight they retreat in an unexpected direction or fail to arrive.And in unit-to-unit combat the balance has tipped even further in favour of quantity over quality. While some units are real game changers the best tactic often seems to be to cluster-rush the enemy with as many low value units as possible (it's certainly the tactic the AI empoys).The shortcoming of Red Dragon's naval battles have already been highlihgted but are worth revisiting. Not only do naval units add nothing to the mix, they are a major distraction. For anyone that's played naval combat classics like Harpoon, Red Dragon naval combat is a joke. Since naval combat is present in all of the campaigns this means that there is no decent way to experience RD as a solo player as you are forced into endless (and pointless) naval slug fests. Further the naval outcomes influence the whole campaign (rightly so) and so you have to endure them to complete the campaign.I hoped for more and I got much much less.I hope Eugen listens to the community, persists and fixes the franchise because there is much promise in it. How long that will take is anyone's guess."
