76561197963448780,Not Recommended,251060,15323467,"Posted: 12 April, 2015",all,Shroom,"Not until the fix the artillery in this game. If you play redfor all you need is 1 - 3 players (depending on game size) to roll a support deck and you win. REDFOR artillery is about 30x as lethal as BLUFOR artillery. Mostly because of rockets, but even their tubed artillery is better. They don't even need to try and in most games can arty random cap points to destroy your command vehicle and usually get in 1-2 hits. Pretty dumb.Edit: Have continued to play this game for months in the hopes it will get better and still wish I could get my money back. The bottom line is that this is very much a game. if you play it hoping to get some kind of wargame simulation out of it you're absolutely wasting your money. The units in most cases are accurate to real life (with exceptions to range for gameplay purposes) but there are some glaring inaccuracies and gameplay balance issues that kind of ruin the game in my opinion.1) The game in GENERAL revolves around a ""quality"" vs ""quantity"" concept. For example, if you're NATO you can expect to get a few REALLY good super units but very low quantity. If you're pact, you can expect to get some good units and a few super units but with exceptionally more availability. From a ""gameplay"" perspective this might make sense but the reality is it scews a lot of things in favor of pact. Bottom line is if you can kill a few of the NATO ""super"" units you're almost guaranteed a win unless you're just an idiot. This also ties into the ""balance vs realism"" that I post below because the reality is the USSR could field more infantry and artillery than NATO but not more helicopters, fixed wing or tanks. However in this game they can.... by a lot.2) Balance vs realism. Bottom line this is not a realistic game. There are a few combos that are near unbeatable in certain situations. For example, NATO patriot missle can snipe red air from miles with little risk even to SEAD. On the other side, russian spetsnatz + VDV combo in a forest is unbeatable by land units. Only chance to win vs that is bombs/napalm/artillery. There are no NATO infantry or vehicles that can defeat that combo unless you want to lose at a roughly 6 to 1 ratio. Combine that with the fact that US basically does not have infantry and you have a very ""gimmicky"" game. I say that the US basically does not have infantry because for the sake of ""balance"" their stats are so horrible that they're actually useless in most cases. The only reason to use US infantry is for their bradley which is barely decent vehicle. The infantry themselves are very close to useless. Combine that with the fact that Delta Force is also the worst SF unit in the game and can kill almost nothing then you will start to see what i mean.Potential: The game has a lot of potential but there are some glaring flaws that still ruin it for a lot of people like myself. Artillery is still a game ruiner, not just a game changer. In low point games it's not really an issue (because no one can afford it). But anything from 3v3 up with a decent amount of points and you can expect to get shelled all game. This is made particularly worse by ""Smerching"" which i reference in my earlier version of my post. This is basically when a player brings multiple cards of rocket artillery and picks a spot on the map where he believes enemy units are and simply hits fire and wipes everything out. This can be gamebreaking particularly early on since the maps use a lot of choke points so you HAVE to go certain ways to get to the front. This makes sniping in early games easy and can essentially end what should be a 40 minute game in the first 40 seconds.Bottom line: Eugen has a lot of work to do with this game before it deserves anyone elses money."
