76561198132246895,Recommended,251060,32664379,Posted: 22 June,all,Gunter,"Turns my computer into a heater, perfect for the harsh Canadian winters 10/10"
,Not Recommended,251060,14458809,"Posted: 13 February, 2015",all,Token Why Boy,"I bought Red Dragon when it was 75% off thinking, ""Wow, what a deal!"" And I guess it was. I wouldn't pay more than $10 for this game, and you shouldn't either, assuming you want to buy it at all.Wargame: Red Dragon is probably a step under AAA. Why would someone not recommend it?Red Dragon is the third installment in the Wargame series, following European Escalation and Airland Battle. In Airland Battle, air units were added, and in Red Dragon, naval units. The air game seemed to fit decently into the meta, but the naval game...is a mess. Eugen's love for dice rolling comes out in a real nasty way, and any semblence of either realistic or tactical naval gameplay is set aside for blobbing up your units and praying that your anti-missile equipment holds out longer than the other guy's.So far as graphics go, yeah, it's a pretty game. It'll take your nice gaming rig and make things look real nice, or you can play it just fine on a potato like mine (just...don't go into those 10v10s if that's a problem).But where this game really drops the ball is in the single player. The campaigns are actually decently-structured---on paper. Consider the ""Medium"" difficulty campaign, Bear vs. Dragon, where you've got your Chinese/N.Korea army in 1979 facing 1984 T-80s and experimental units. This wouldn't be too big of an issue if you just fought a small number of them, but Eugen's AI compensates for certain shortcomings in AI programming by having it both be omniscient and have several factors more deployment points than it has any right to at the start of a match.This is a huge problem in naval games, where the enemy can deploy its 500 point flagships with an entire supporting navy *and* air support while you're lucky to get out a few frigates and some meager anti-ship missile defenses. And because, as we've already established, maneuvering and tactical combat gets one nowhere in the game, particularly against the AI, who fields a vastly superior force bar none, every game, what was a problem becomes a gamebreaking flaw.The ironic thing is, the sort of naval warfare that it looks like Eugen was going for would do great in a WWII setting. But by pushing in the opposite direction, I fear Eugen jumped the shark with Airland Battle, and it's all downhill from there.While I like the idea of taking regiments and attaching battalions and companies to them to make your force much more than ALB's ""here, have an army and let's tag team it up"" campaign, you're still woefully underequipped to deal with most of what the enemy will throw at you unless you specifically pick out the one little hard counter company, which often means having prior knowledge about what you're going to be facing several turns in advance.A common motif in Red Dragon is the necessity of recon. Unfortunately, while map sizes seem larger, point compensation wasn't considered, meaning the maps are now far too spread out for your unit visibility. This is again a compounded issue when you remember that the AI is omniscient. I've always felt that all units could use a visibility increase (both recon and normal units), but I know that's an argument made in vain, because that's a core mechanic to the game. But the amount of times I've had a recon unit one-shot the moment he spotted an enemy vehicle leads me to believe something funny is going on, and it just leaves me with a bad taste.In brief: the only reason I would recommend buying Red Dragon would be because you have friends that play it, or want to get into the multiplayer scene. But for the love of all that is holy, stay off the chat. It's unmodded, so if you think you can walk in and make a few friends, you've got another thing coming. If you're entirely new to the Wargame series and want to try it out, I would highly recommend ALB over Red Dragon. Yes, the AI still cheats there, but there's far less units to dig through, and the campaigns there are a bit more friendly. The single-player modes look great on paper, but Eugen's AI makes them a horrible experience, and the modding support simply isn't there to fix it."
