76561198056010838,Not Recommended,251060,12444567,"Posted: 10 October, 2014",all,Karter Blackpaw,"Trying to take a much more modernized redux on the old turn-based strategy game ""People's General"" from SSI in 1998; this RTS just sadly falls flat despite good visuals. If you're new to this series, you'll have a very hard time trying to figure out what to do since there's no official tutorial system in the game aside from reading large paragraphs of ""what to do"" in-game, and that's it. Nothing more, nothing less. It won't show you how the game works or offer any idea to somebody wanting to try this. Campaign's are too difficult due to false difficulties that even going against a ""Normal"" AI will seem like you're going against a ""Hard"" or ""Very Hard"" opponent. Then once in-game, if you were looking for a great actiony styled RTS where you can see the carnage and explosions from units moving about like what you saw in the trailers for this game, well you're not gonna get that. It's impossible to see any of the units in-game due to how you have to keep track of EVERY detail of EVERY unit as you zoom back to the moon in order to see what you need to command and manage. Granted this is a nice feature which is rare to find in many games. But overall having to babysit so many units across big maps give you zero chances to actually see your units or look cloesly at the battle. It is the equivelant of playing ""Axis and Allies"" the board game in real time with boxes moving about the screen to tell you the name of units. This is sad since the detail that was put into these units is quite impressive, especially when you have 15+ nations to choose and assort with. As for the menu system, good luck trying to find and set up a game with a friend. As for the menu side of things, you are REQUIRED to make an account for this game due to it being a 3rd party company. Yes this is a small annoyance, but then trying to add your friend after setting up these accounts is frustrating since the adding buttons don't work unless you open them in a specific way.  I enjoy most RTS's, like Command and Conquer, Total War, and others, but this one doesn't do it right with all these small problems. It was a nice try, but sometimes the most basic things of playing an RTS need to be shown better."
