76561198064434994,Recommended,251060,11050385,"Posted: 3 July, 2014",all,Kloudwolf,"Wargame: Red Dragon, is for all intents and purposes, A step forward in the series with one foot, and a step back with the other. One of my favorite pieces from AirLand Battle, the Coop campaign, has been left out of this game. If you're looking for a fun strategy to play with your friends, get AirLand Battle before this game. That being said, the SP Campaign of this game is exemplary. From moving whole armies across a map, you get even more control by being able to create your own army from units. You can have a supply company supporting an infantry regiment and tank company, with a specialized unit of recon flying overhead. Buying strike planes to stick it to your enemy or fighters to cover your own skin, it's up to you. Every single unit you lose is lost for the rest of the war, so strategy and keeping your powerful tanks and expensive bombers alive is a must. What you lose one turn may be your downfall later.On another note, Wargame is known for two things: A game chat which has the maturity of the worst CoD players you can imagine, and people who instead of playing legitly, go for Artillery Spam and massing cheap tanks and rushing them at you. Those people are a horrible blemish on what is in my opinion one of the best strategy games ever. Multiplayer matches can net you a feeling of accomplishment by beating a tough opponent, and can also leave you wanting to toss your computer out the window.Overall, I give this game a firm reccomendation. I've played both games in the series before this, and can say that what lessons I've learned from all three games have made me a better player in Red Dragon. Right now the only thing I want from this game before the Devs move on to their next title is a Coop mode to play with my friends. But they already have my money, so I guess it's a moot point."
76561197972464843,Recommended,251060,11021496,"Posted: 2 July, 2014",all,Dwight,"Wargame Red Dragon is a strategy simulation that is the closest approximation of modern combat I have ever seen. The game plays extremely well. It is possible for a weak deck played well to destroy an opponent with better weapons and weak tactics. I recently played a game where an opponent attacked down an avenue of approach and was slaughtered in about 10 seconds through a combination of concealed vehicles, entrenched infantry, and heavy bombers.The only dynamic criticism I have relate to realism.1. If you capture enemy supplies in real life you will only really be able to use the fuel and the food. Shells, ammunition, missiles, and vehicle repair parts are available in captured stockpiles unlike the real world.2.  In real live having an air force with 5 different types of aircraft is much more expensive then one type of aircraft. I would rather have a system that would allow you to  select a type of aircraft and then multiple configurations of that aircraft. It would add complexity though.3. Helicopters once called in with infantry are almost useless. Allow players to return them to base for a resource refund.4. If i have a deck that incorporates Light Armored Vehicles (LAVs) for most vehicle types then I should get a bonus on cost and availability because in real life it is a lot cheaper to maintain one type of vehicle then 5.These are really nitpicky issues. The only substantial issue I do have is that you have to be careful who you play. It is very easy to ""Stack the Deck"" in a multiplayer game. Some players with high win to loss ratios appear more skilled at picking the right team then actually playing the game. Not to disparrage the multitude of very skilled players in the community. Most can relate to getting stuck on an unbalanced team and getting crushed. It really isn't a lot of fun. But it is in keeping with Sung Tzu's strategies which advocate ""knowing your enemy and yourself and only fighting at the time and place of your choosing when conditions are favorable."" I guess this means that even the calibre of player in Wargame: Red Dragon is superior to that of other strategy games."
