76561198043503114,Recommended,251060,17120675,"Posted: 19 July, 2015",all,Fixter-Upper,"In short:- Brilliant number of new units and Nations with a distinct feel but with a shallower learning curve than previous titles.- Tons of new Air Units to play with, which look and function the best i've ever seen in RTS.- Dismal Naval combat, with massively unsatisfying, anarchic, high-loss encounters as standard.- Excellent campaign scenarios, with varying degrees of difficulty and historical backing (if like me you're a sucker for             that sort of thing :P ).- Multi-level battles that function well; new air elements and marine landings working well together.- Game results from battles still incredibly confusing on the strategic overview, with entire forces being destroyed despite in game performance that would seem to dictate otherwise.It's been apparent, even to the most unobservant of gamers, that the Wargame series has been becoming more and more complex as it evolves. First, starting off with ground combat, then introducing the AirLand Battle elements of Close Air Support and challenging you think more '4th Dimensionally!!!' but now it seems to have become a victim of this very formula. Simply put, if you want a good idea of the naval combat in Red Dragon, watch the very first gameplay trailer on the games page on Steam Store: it's unadulterated chaos and I find myself auto-resolving every naval encounter (which is really unsatisfying since the computer often screws it up even worse than I do and I feel like i'm cheating). This is a real shame, and while it may very well be true of naval combat in the 21st Century it leaves you with the distinctly unsatisfactory choice as a commander to sacrifice the bulk of your fleet to achieve victory in the short term, or just allow yourself to be destroyed. You rarely find yourself in a position of real numerical or technical superiority (which adds a welcome challenge) but this makes encounters overwhelmingly phyrric (and it may just be the rage talking but the Soviet/Communist Forces really do seem to have simply BETTER Naval Units) and i find myself feeling that instead of giving commands i'm just watching the calamity unfold.Whilst I may be a self confessed softie in RTS games who tries to preserve the lives of his pixelated troops (nearly put 'pixelated privates' there ahem...) even I have a ruthless streak that will sacrifice to achieve victory in a game like Red Dragon, which I love in spite of it's flaws. However, I balk at the level that it asks me to be ruthless in naval combat, as there's something distinctly phyrric about EVERY SINGLE BATTLE, which is really unsatisfying as a gamer. If you have the ruthlessness necessary to fight like the computer does in Red Dragon and will sacrifice Naval units with reckless abandon, then you'll do much better than me.But, if you discount the ship-to-ship combat of Red Dragon, the naval elements function very well indeed; be it with dozens of amphibious vehicles descending on a beach in Korea or Japan or having a fleet of monitors sit off the port you are trying to capture, giving the enemy forces an almighty pasting. But Red Dragon's real step forward is the massive influx of new units and factions, each worked out to the finest details. It can take some time to acclimatise to a new set of Nations, and they still only say the same lines in different languages, but it adds so many new units that your options in game are much richer. The F-117 is a new favourite of mine! Stealth bombers and waves of planes armed with a myriad of new weapons give you the options now that AirLand Battle have introduced you to the basics of Air Command and it works astoundingly well! Forces available are much larger than ever before as well, especially if you play as China or North Korea, whose cheap-as-chips approach to units can be great fun.Basically, it's brilliant! If you liked AirLand Battle and want extra challenge, new units and don't mind skipping the naval combat if you find it as irritating as me; then the newest installment is definitely for you!"
