76561197997127013,Recommended,251060,19443039,"Posted: 2 December, 2015",all,Spartanz1170,"This game is a great example of RTS gameplay similar to the Total War and World in Conflict, no resource gathering just deploy units and go for it. However there is a great amount of risk and just as much for reward, in Wargame the more expensive the unit it will generally do better but losing it will cost you dearly if you do not maintain an adequete supply line. The same goes in reverse for more low cost units, the cheaper the unit the more crappy it is, but losing a cheap unit won't hurt you as much if you can keep up a reserve of troops to take their place.Micromanaging is key in this game, no not like Starcraft II Korean tier of micromanagement but rather you need to maintain a degree of spatial awareness. Grouping certain units to hotkeys is key to sucessful micromanaging as well knowing when to use these units among other things. To learn more about the gameplay mechanics and features try and look for the beginners guide to Wargame Red Dragon, be warned though it's 200 pages long so patience is key.TL;DR: IT'S A GOOD GAME, LEARN TO GITGUD, AND BE PATIENT, ESPECIALLY WITH THE PLAYERBASE."
