76561198076586372,Recommended,251060,12804308,"Posted: 5 November, 2014",all,A Cloudy Sheep,"Long story short: The Wargame series contains the best multiplayer real-time strategy games out there. Red Dragon is the latest iteration; the new features range from bad-but-ignorable (Navy) to marginal improvements (filter options in the armory) and in itself might not be a compelling reason to go for Red Dragon. Still Red Dragon has the largest player base by far, which is obviously what you want in multiplayer.Long story long:This is easily the best real time strategy game there is, precisely because it deviates from the norms of the genre in interesting ways. Also relatively unique in its late-cold-war setting, which I enjoyed.Firstly, in the standard game mode you win the game by destroying, say, 6000 points worth of enemy units. This has two implications. It encourages you to be cautious with your units so you do not feed points to your enemy, and you need to carefully balance your forces between different costs. For example losing a 120-point tank by assaulting a 10-point infantry unit in a town is a serious setback, as it just brought your enemy 120 point closer to victory.The net effect of this is that the game can actually be rather slow-paced and thought through. Especially in smaller games towards the end it can result in a cat-and-mouse game, where you try to snatch some enemy points while being careful not to poke your head out too far. It’s overall a much more thoughtful process than most RTS games. However, note that there are other game modes that are closer to the genre standard.The other distinguishing factor of Wargame is the scope and complexity of the underlying mechanics. Each unit has about 20 or so variables: basic things like speed, intermediary stuff like frontal, side, rear and top armour, and advanced stuff like whether the tertiary weapon of a unit has active radar emissions that can be targeted by dedicated anti-radar weapons. All of this results in a delicate system of counters that is not just unit-based as in most RTS games, but also highly circumstantial. A MILAN-2 anti-tank-guided-missile-team is a great counter against tanks – as long as it is stationary, can use its higher range, and is not too distracted (e.g. from being under small arms or mortar fire). A STRV-103B tank lacks a turret and stabilizers, so it cannot move very well while on the move – but it has good frontal armour, and a ‘kinetic energy’ gun, so if you can hide it in a hedgerow it can wreak havoc in an ambush.This is not very newbie friendly, but it is rewarding. Understanding the various units (there are several hundred) and the way they interact is more important than being very fast with your mouse. You do not need the memorize the precise range of the main gun of a T-72A, but you should know that an IGLA is a infra-red anti-air missile, so moving a helicopter close is not a smart idea (unless, maybe you supress the anti-air with mortars first). This is especially important, because the game uses a deck-system. You can pre-select a number of different units that you field during a battle, so you have to spend some time building deck that is well rounded and allows you to react to specific threads. Personally, I find this to be as much fun as the actual game.There is no base-building in this game, there is only one resource which is earned by occupying rather large areas on the map, and no typical fog-of-war: You are likely to spot a huge tank or chopper at quite some distance, but a unit with a low detection-value can drive by an infantry platoon in a wood without noticing. So you really do not know whether you do not see something because there is nothing there, or whether it’s just hidden well enough.Lastly, I praise this game mainly for the multiplayer. Single player campaigns and skirmishes exist, and the AI is alrightish, but the real fun is in multiplayer, between anything from 1-vs-1 to 10-vs-10.A great game that borders on turn-based strategy such as Panzer General, while maintaining the momentum and liveliness of a real-time game. Buy if you enjoy actual strategy over clicks-per-second gamin"
76561198031455290,Recommended,251060,12863776,"Posted: 9 November, 2014",all,Qbus_88,"Congratulations, you stumbled upon the latest installment of probably  the best RTS series of its time.I Absolutely adore this game and the series as a whole, one of the very best strategy titles around. It's detailed and realistic enough to be engaging but not too focused on micro management to be off putting, I think they struck a great balance. Graphics are very nice and you don't even need to sell your soul to be able to afford a PC capable of running it decently.Be warned though: The learning curve is VERY steep and it will take you quite some time and studying the units to be successful. I actually read up on many of the units in the game on wikipedia, this does help but needless to say this costs a lot of time an especially at first it may be a bit frustrating. I will give you a short summary of my opinion of Red Dragon specifically, please do note that I only play single player.I'm happy to say that the game offers enough depth in SP to be worth buying for that alone. More and more games these days think they can slim down SP content in favor of MP. While Red Dragon has MP the single player is very enjoyable and more than enough challenge at times at least for me. When compared to AirLand battle it must be said that Red Dragon doesn't offer that much more than its predecessor. The hyped up aspect was the naval battles and they fall woefully short when compared to the depth the rest of the game offers. If you're new to this series: wait until it's on sale and go nuts on AirLand battle first. It's cheaper and gameplay wise not much different at all. I like the Asian theatre which is why Red Dragon is ultimately my favorite title in the Wargame series but purely from a value for money point of view, being as objective as I can be:If you're new to this series, try AirLand battle first, if you like that one I can pretty much guarantee you'll like Red Dragon but it's not worth €40 (or $ or whatever you pay for it with) because it simply didn't add enough content for that. Wait until it's around the €25 region. By that time you'll probably have gotten over most of the difficulty curve as well if you buy the previous one now. One final tip regarding that difficulty curve: There's a reason why every army in the world switched to a Combined Arms doctrine(http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combined_arms)around WW2 and kept using it ever since."
