,Recommended,251060,11568788,"Posted: 5 August, 2014",all,salt.  ŘicӪchèt,"I'm not usually an RTS player, I find them all too clicky and stats driven, knowing DPS and modifiers etc. However I am a military enthusiast and enjoy realism in games. This is what sets Wargame series apart from many other RTS.An excellent blend of current and past nations, historical and some modern conflicts and full ""deck"" customisation allows anyone from any nation to get involved (and at some points, a little patriotic) As an Australian I don't often get a chance to see games featuring our World Class Special Forces SASR or Bushmaster APC's mixed in with other nations, however with nations such as Australia, Canada, Brittain, West Germany, Japan, Korea, CSSR, Poland, USA, Russia, Czech Republic...  the list goes on!When customising a deck to take on either AI or Multiplayer skirmishes of land capture, total destruction or an interesting shared currency mode known as Economy, you have vast options on wether you want close air support, helicopters, infantry deployed via land, air or sea. You can explore tanks, reconnisance snipers, artillery and MRLS systems and even Navy to some degree. It's an incredibel mix that really suits any gamer style with strengths and waeknesses to every deck and nation. Not to mention the Prototype vehicles the the amazing Nighthawk for the USA with a deadly and precise guided bomb, or the Russian KA-50 Akula Tank Killer!The community is very quick to judge, and the learning curve was steep! Reading forums and guides on playstyles and strengths really helps you blend into the battle. However persist the first few ""Ranks"" and you realise the tide of battle can easily be changed if you know what to look for and use team strategiesThe only downsides are that because they've themed the game to follow the 80's/90's style computer screen they have made a very backwards game room chat and game preview facility you have to ""join"" and look at each players stats individually to understand if the teams are balanced or not. One window for chat between your game room/general chat/friends is also rather annoying. The other downside is there are often connection issues that result in one person leaving at the start of the game, the points are redistributed, but if your team can overcome this then quite often you can counter quickly with the higher income.Wargame Red Dragon is an excellent multiplayer, great unit selection and balanced gameplay that will leave you asking where the time has gone to. Its a nail biting ride through every game with fluid battle dynamics, excellent realism and quite a little bit of pride when your team overcomes the enemy! I'd highly recommend Wargame franchise to anyone interested in a little more than base building and spamming units.9/10~R"
