,Recommended,251060,14931253,"Posted: 17 March, 2015",all,Wild Cat,"If you're looking for a casual RTS don't come near this game, go for R.U.S.E. instead, it is a great RTS also by Eugen Systems and perfect for LAN parties and casual rounds of RTS fun (my review).On the other hand, if you're prepared to put up with a steep learning curve and get into a very detailed RTS experience, the like of which have never been seen before in a video game, then you are in the right place.What Eugen Systems seem to be doing is a daring step to change what we imagine when we hear ""RTS"", the level of details is unrivaled. For those reasons, I couldn't come up with pros and cons, just ""features"", they are the first things you'll probably notice when you go from Red-Alert RTS to Wargame RTS, some bugged me but after a while I realized I was just playing with the wrong mentality so I'll leave it to your discretion to decide if they are good or bad.The Features:A huge selection of units, grouped by nationality (lots of those, too) and by era. The amount of research put into that section gives the game its taste.The campaigns, though few in number, are very well made depicting real, modern struggles. There is a lot to learn and a lot to enjoy in those.Selecting any unit in Wargame showstactical detailsthat you're probably not used to see, things like range, accuracy, rate of fire and ammunition for each weapon that unit carries. The same unit might have different armaments and different experience levels and act totally different.You have to createdecksof your units to play during a game, the deck section, in my opinion, is an added strategy battle, one that you have to win before even going to the battle.Logistics:That's the word that will make you challenge the nearest wall with your head, repeatedly. Every unit uses fuel and ammunition for each gun it carries, when it fires a round, it has one round less and, you guessed it, those things run out and ""someone"" (you) has to keep logistic routes open to resupply them. Also, your main supplies are not limitless so even with the perfect logistics routes you might still find the wall a good place for your head to bounce upon.Reconis the second factor that contributes to the depth of tactics involved in Wargame. Most units have limited optics and they need scouts to uncover and identify units nearby. Recon units make it possible for a tank to hit at maximum range and might save your troops from a deadly trap. That being said, recon units are not created equal and even the best ones will not see deep into dense jungles and inside cities, which leads us to the next feature:Infantry. While useless in most RTS games, infantry units in the deck of a worthy Wargame player could well turn the tides in a battle. The variation of infantry is astonishing and they can be transported by APCs or by helicopters for fast, deep operations. The best part is their stealth inside jungles and cities. There is nothing more satisfying than having a couple of elite Seal team sneak right next to an enemy artillery undetected. Also, training counts. A lot.Artilleryis where I start going really mad, I hate them and their long range BUT, the satisfying part is that in Wargame, those tin-monsters have a ""dispersion"" factor and use up a lot of resources, so much so that I usually let an enemy artillery barrage live just so it drains their resourcesand that's a tactical move you can't do in other RTS games.Navy Unitsthough not often usable, are quite nice to play with and the right ones could considerably boost your land prowess.ConclusionWargame bolds the ""S"" in ""RTS"" and Eugen Systems is redifining the genre. In Wargame, you'll need more tactics than fast clicks and more strategy than amassing armadas. You'll find very fast that the most expensive tank is not invincible and airplanes obey the rules of gravity pretty well if you don't know your enemy's air defenses. Rolling with a lot of troops into the enemy base will almost never guarantee you a victory and the same tactics, even the same decks will never be the perfect ones on all maps or in all scenarios! And well, that's the best part of this game."
