,Recommended,251060,14479733,"Posted: 15 February, 2015",all,DubMeister,"WARNING! DO NOT expect this game to be like any other RTS game. If you are expecting this to be similar to Total War, Company of Heroes, World in Conflict, or Men of War: Assault Squad 2, this game is not for you. This RTS is a very serious tactical and strategic game. Every mistake you make and misstep in preparation will cost you dearly. Though, in contrast, every successful push made may very well change the tide of battle. It has a large learning curve, but after some determination, it's worth it.I tried out European Escalation and Airland Battles in the past. I sucked at it horribly and couldn't finish the campaign. Yet, I still enjoyed its unique gameplay. I bought Red Dragon because it was on sale and I was interested in trying out the additional gameplay content. Knowing the basics of how to play from EE and ALB already, I jumped straight into campaign thinking that my experience from TW, CoH, WiC, and MoW: AS2 would surely have improved my skills compared to my first time in Wargame... I couldn't have been more wrong... My forces were obliterated within the first minute of the match... Lost to an easy AI on the very first mission of the easy campaign.This time, I wasn't going to give up on a game I couldn't win. I watched a few battles to see the tactics and strategies players used to win against both AI and human opponents from their deployment patterns to mid-battle decision making. I was also lucky enough to find a veteran player willing to give me tips on deck building, guide me through some basic combat techniques, and invite me to his group of other veteran players who would advise me on how to play. After a little more practice, everything changed. I started to win more than lose and do an efficient job.In total, I only found two cons in this game. The minor one would be the naval battles which are just clunky and follow a last-one-standing-wins rule rather than the tactical combat that is regular land battles. The most negative con I find would be the rather newbie-unfriendly community of veteran players. I'm not saying all veterans are unwelcoming, but if you're new, you're very likely to run into matches where you're kicked for being too low ranked. You have a better chance of finding a match by joining a very large match like 10vs10 because they don't bother to check everyone's levels. Though with inexperience, you wouldn't contribute much to the team in such a match. The best way to gain early experience is by creating a server of your own and title it ""Newbies only.""9.5/10 Would learn how to play rather than do college homework again."
