76561198015475346,Recommended,251060,13214848,"Posted: 3 December, 2014",all,Perilos,"What if World War 3 happened between 1970 and 1990… multiple times?I think that is the question which Eugen System thought first about, as they started to create the concept of the Wargame franchise.“Wargame: Red Dragon” is the third part of the franchise.If you ever thought about to be a commander of military operations, this game is for you. Eugen Systems is very accurate with the arsenal of weapons they offer to you, to do your job on a big battlefield.But it’s not like a Command and Conquer or a Starcraft. You’re not “in the action” like in that classic strategic games. You command the whole operation.There is no base building. The only building you have in that game is a supply depot, which you deploy at the start of the match. You take care of the supply of your troops and you only have a limited army. Your troops need ammo, gas and repair. If you don’t watch your supply line, your army result in a sitting duck and total destruction.Unlike in a Starcraft match for example, you don’t decide the winner in a single battle. There are multiple hot spots and you fight on different fronts. Positioning, mobility and tactical knowledge is the key to survive and win a battle. Tanks have different hit zones with different defence values. Different weapon systems deal different damage to different armour or units.The realism factor is high. The community is “hardcore” and you should have a little bit real world tactical knowledge. The learning curve is pretty straight and high. If you want to invest a few bucks in that game, know that you will hate the game. You hate it, but you want to beat it. Your first match you will win, will feel like you won the whole war.The game features infantry, tanks, vehicles, planes, helicopters and warships in different categories. Your troops are from different times. So your “deck” (army build) features different tanks. For example the West German Bundeswehr shows up on the battlefield in the early game with Kpz Keiler from the 60s and end their match with Leopard 2A5 tanks. The key is not always to bring the biggest tank to every battle. Every unit has a point value. To win a match you destroy points. So your 50 points tank isn’t strong as a 120 point one, but you feel less slapped if your assault on the enemy defence line is destroyed by two helicopters in one run. Combined warfare is the basic of every match. If you throw tank after tank into the battle, you win nothing. The enemy simple counters with a spam of helicopters or other anti-tank units. And tanks have many enemies in that game.I recommend the 200 page guide in the guide section of that game. It helps a lot to understand the game. The core of the game is: Warfare as realistic as possible.I really enjoy the game for 1-2 hours in a row on a rainy day at home. Let your enemies bath in tears, because of your superior chess move or burst in tears, if you thought you win the battle but end in a napalm disaster, watching how your troops burn like candles.The game features a few campaigns with made up scenarios. The intro movies are nice mad and explain the situation to you. The campaigns itself are chained destruction battles. This is the core gameplay of that game. It can be boring after a while.If you think about multiplayer, forget it. The people are moping the floor with you, until you aren’t a hardcore player yourself. Play with friends for the best multiplayer experience.The AI makes a good job. Depending on the situation on the political map in the campaign they rip you off or get steamrolled. But most times you face an overwhelming army in points and really need to think about which troops you bring to the battle. I really enjoy the campaigns. But I didn’t beat a single one.If you enjoy grand battle real time strategy games, this is the game for you. Play it, love it and be happy about every battle you win. But keep in mind, that the game only centre around the battle. There are no different objectives. You make your own to win.8/10"
