,Recommended,251060,27222289,"Posted: 24 November, 2016",all,Von Steinberg,"Probably the best mix of micro- and macro-management there is. By ripping out the base-building aspect of traditional RTS-games and replacing it with a preparation similar to card games, the matches themselves focus on what's important: The action.The game allows for either massive, energy draining battles that require the best you can give to keep your units alive AND manage your side of the battle, as well as more laid back, tactically demanding small-scale battles where every single unit you get is important and has to be kept alive at all costs. Then there's of course the more tightly packed action of the smaller modes (less players) and the true test of your abilities in a ranked 1v1.The game is still kept alive and supported by the developers, although recently that means mostly paid DLCs. Considering the longevity of the game, that is understandable and seeing that the DLC is not necessary to experience the full game and compete well in it, that's also okay.Sadly there is no option to completely shut off the text window visible when outside a match - usually there is nothing but flamewars and stupid Hitler-discussions going on. This game does have a ""mute"" button for individual players though (unlike the predecessors), so it is possible to filter at least the worst offenders from going on your cookie..."
