76561197999843404,Recommended,251060,23662845,"Posted: 19 June, 2016",all,griffon926,"To be  blunt, this game should have redefined the genre, but the lack of good publicity and attention left this game woefully underadvertised.The simple... this game is the Homeworld of modern/cold war RTS's (yea, that damn good, forget World in Conflict).Here's why:Hundreds of realistically rendered and balanced unitsA set of well crafted and historically based ""What if"" WWIII campaigns with scaling difficultyNo basebuilding BS (I personally don't care for Starcraft/C&C) as basebuilding detracts from the real STRATEGY of fire, maneuver, and support any real general considers.  You have points, you get units with these points.  More zones you control with commanders, the faster the points roll in.The Total War style campaign map, with your regiments you order in from offmap and refit with campaign points is plenty enough supply/ ""basebuilding""Excellent multiplayer experience with customizable ""Decks"" (regiments)Fairly easy to learn, difficult to master, as any good game should be.  The tutorials go through the mechanics of the game rather well, but it's up to you to learn the strategy.Battles cover whole scope of WWIII combat: Land battles with tank charges into ATGM launcher/infantry ambushes under artillery fire, dogfights/air support overhead, and a naval battle unfolding in the adjacent sea.---So in short, this is a Total War 'esque campaign map mixed with modern themed Supreme Commander scale battles (sans base building)This is what World In Conflict could have and should have been.Finally, if this game is commonly used in Military Schools and ROTC for Tactical/Strategic training, you know they're getting it right.So come on you armchair generals, time to get yo Patton on!"
