76561197998027846,Recommended,251060,22378426,"Posted: 12 April, 2016",all,Ellemann357,"Absolutely brilliant, solid and fun RTS. Its got a steep learning curve, compared to most other rts titles. Its got depth and complexity, mastering this game will require the player to learn what specific units really do, and when to use them. The sheer amount of units that can be implemented in a force, and the diversity among them, makes it possible to tailor an army to specific tactical preferences. Hell, the deck manager is fun!Also, as mentioned by others; Quite entertaining lobby chat, probably the most hostile social-arena on this planet."
76561198006708850,Recommended,251060,22436721,"Posted: 15 April, 2016",all,Loves2Splooge,"If you really like history, especially contemporary history, then youll love this game. While it doesnt convey history to you, the amount of content on war units is so immersive that you will really appreciate how complex, massive and well designed these machines were and the massive part they played in history between 1949 and 1991. The game is very strategy based and you can't assume to win just by spamming.... Okay sometimes you can, but that gets old quick and against a competent player it probably wont work. Its much more satisfying to atleast emplore some degree of strategy and try to minimize losses. Or you can go totally russian and try to smash enemy lines with numbers alone. There is a massive, massive, massive, amount of units, and within them, a massive, massive, amount of depth. This alone provides a huge amount of replay value, so long as you enjoy RTS games to start with. Here are some of the most important things I have learned so far. 4.15.16- Massive learning curve.a. little help from game in introducing you to the game and how to play.b. massive amount of content is daunting and discouraging.c. this is overcome only by trial and error, when you start to get what your doing, the games layers and depth will be more obvious and this is really where the game begins... probably a good 10-15 hours in is when id say youll start to actually realize wtf your doing.- Prepare to read and analyze hundreds of different unit selections that are seemingly similar.- The differences between them, while seemingly small, are actually very important to distinguish, proper selections will offer most efficent use of money and more knowledge about how the unit should be played.- Never underestimate the value of infantry, in cities, and outside of them too.- Realize the necessity for recon units. *** without sight, you cant see enemy units and youll just see your guys blow up.- Realize the value of accurate, efficient, long ranged artillery.- Efficiently choose aircraft (being theyre so much money, really test them out and pick the best option, a really expensive plane with only one availble might not be a good choice versus a moderate plane selection with 3 avaible).- Realize that tanks are proably not as important as you thought they might be, and should be de-emphasized.- Again... RECON RECON RECON.Great game with massive depth, if you like RTS' you love it :D"
