,Recommended,251060,30339940,Posted: 5 March,all,mika fuchs,"tl;dr Wonerful little RTS with virtually infinite possibilities- would certainly recommend, but only to players who are willing to spend some time learning mechanics.Wargame: Red Dragon is an awesome little realistic RTS that simulates war on a scale rarely seen in such a genre, spanning miles upon miles of territory. It forces one to use real logic and strategies to outfox and eliminate the enemy. For example, approaching the enemy without combined arms is a disaster waiting to happen- e.g tanks without AA will easily die to helos and planes, infantry without armoured support gets obliterated by tanks, etc.The game can be split into two parts- building 'decks', in which a player builds a force using 'cards' of various units, and actual combat. The battles, on the other hand, are (quite literally) bloody fantastic. Every small detail from the whistle of the Katyusha as a salvo of death gracefully flies across the map to the empty cartridges ejecting out of an infantryman's rifle is faithfully modeled, as Soviet-backed Warsaw Pact and allied countries engage in a massive showdown of epic proportions against NATO nations and their supporters in the beautifully depicted landscape of East Asia. A huge number of units from both sides feature, compelling the player to make several crucial decisions that could turn the tide of battle- whether it be to risk sending an unsupported force against what you hope is the last thing the enemy has, or to pin your hopes on a small squad of recon infantry to find and take out the enemy's command vehicle before they can call out more reinforcements.But something one can really appreciate about this game is the diversity of the units, allowing the player to send out more or less any kind of unit fielded during the era of the 80-90s- whether it be surplus WWII-era T-34/85 tanks supporting North Korean reservists armed with Chinese PPSh-41s, all the way to the cream-of-the-crop T-90 tank and elite troops armed with grenade launchers. This could lead to some interesting realistic strategies, such as sending out cheap 'meatshield' tanks to weaken enemy defenses and waste their ammunition, before deploying a proper, competent task force to finish 'em off.Of course, like any other RTS, the game suffers from a couple of balancing issues, such as a pathetically underpowered North Korean military (even though it's 1980) and a rather controversial DLC pack, but otherwise most nations are similarly competent against eachother. Usual issues such as kiting isn't very common, since ranges are very strictly controlled (e.g all tanks in the same class have the same engagement range) but issues such as the infamous ""helo spam"" (self-explanatory, some jackass sends a ton of Hinds your way, can (sometimes) be dealt with by spamming your own AA but unrealistic and not very fun nonetheless) remain. Also worthy of note is the extremely shortened engagement distance in this game- the longest ranged tanks in the game have a maximum range of 2.275km.However, the game really isn't new-player friendly. The community is your best bet for learning this game- the ""tutorials"" in W:RD are among the worst I've seen, simply being pure text about how to use the menu and introducing the naval units, with nothing actually explaining how to fight! Thankfully, an AI skirmish mode featuring some of the most incompetent AI I've ever seen exists, so that can be used as a stepping stone. Many guides exist on the Steam and Eugen forums about how to actually play, along with many excellent videos one can find on YouTube.Overall, in conclusion, this game is great albeit slightly flawed, but it's a perfect fit for RTS fans and military enthusiasts of the Cold War. Granted however, it's quite difficult and frustrating- but playing it properly will reward you with hours upon hours of fun. Oh, and one last thing-Expect most of those hours to be in menus.Trust me."
