76561197980770496,Recommended,251060,30373768,Posted: 7 March,all,Mr Schroeder,"Wargame Red Dragon is not a tradional RTS game altough technically it is a real time strategy game. There is no basebuilding or resource gathering.  The decision making necessary to be successful at it can be equally fast paced but the gameplay itself is slower. This is due to the unit movement speeds, where planning in advance is necessary because units can take several minutes to reach the desired locations. On larger maps a unit will run out of fuel before reaching the otherside of the map. Fuel? Yes the game features logistics. Ammunition, fuel and parts for repair.The singleplayer campaign is unremarkable and frankly its gameplay is bland. In skirmish modes on some maps the cheating a.i. has such an advantage that you will likely need to create a deck just for that map. What is a deck? A deck is simply a collection of units from the games vast database that can be called into battle. This means that not every unit that a nation possesses can be called into battle.There are a lot of units available some good some very bad, but ultimately unit cost will often determine whether a player really wants to fill a spot in the deck with the best unit or a cheaper and less effective unit. Stronger units are only available in less quantity. Essentially this means that even if a player can afford an expensive unit in battle, if only one is available in the deck and he already called it, then no more can be called! Each powerful unit must therefore be used with precision and protected.So how do players pay for units if there is no resource gathering? Well there are points that are generally affected by the locations that are controlled on the map. This means games can be altered depending on terrain and starting points to favour one deck over another. For example cheap unaffective infantry may be excellent to gain ground in a game with few starting points and lots of buildings.The game has a steep learning curve because it allows for many creative approaches and tactics. Some people might find the necessary micromanagement that is an essential part of the game problematic; A.I. tends to choose horrible paths when spawned, radar equipment must be turned off manually to avoid anti-radar weapons, artillery will never change locations on their own after firing. Planes will often take the worst evacuation routes imaginable.  The game isn't a simple hit point system and features some RnG elements resulting in some unfortunate battle events on occasion. As an example armour varies in effectiveness depending on a tank's alignment (side, front, back, top). This means a blind Artillery strike on a location can sometimes destroy some expensive tanks. Can you Imagine a cheap light tank hitting a mamoth tank in Red alert 1 and destroying it in one shot? In wargame red dragon this exact scenario will also occur sometimes. Ouch!General infantry play an important role in the game as in real life. Tanks are not immune to a hidden infantry group's short range a.t. weapons. Specialized a.t. and a.a. infantry units can be devastating. Air power, artillery, and tanks all serve realistic roles. Mortars can be used to stun enemies before an advance or to simply cover a unit with smoke. Napalm and cluster munitions can also be utilized. Essentially the game has a lot of diverse units each with different tactical purposes. If any of this sounds appealing you will likely enjoy the game.If you are looking for a traditional rts with a strong single player campagin then avoid this!  If you want to experience a unique strategy game with a solid multiplayer experience then its worth trying this game, flaws and all."
